<P>
OHIO HYDROPLANE RACE DELAYED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
EVANSVILLE, Ind. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
High water levels of the Ohio River caused organizers today to postpone the 
Thunder on the Ohio unlimited hydroplane race scheduled this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
It is the first time since 1981 that the race has been postponed. Under the 
revised schedule, qualifying will be conducted July 7 and 8, and racing will 
begin at noon on July 9. 
</P>
<P>
Jan Theubach, director of the Freedom Festival, said the U.S. Army Corps of 
Engineers has projected that the river will crest at 35.7 feet on Thursday, the 
day before qualifying was to have begun. "If the river is higher than 22 feet, 
we can't hold the race," Theubach said. 
</P>
<P>
The problem is not that the river is too deep, she explained. "It's the pits, 
that's all," she said. "The crews have to be able to set the cranes out, and if 
the concrete's under water, you can't set the cranes out." 
</P>
</TEXT>
