<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
COMPUTE ASSOCIATES TO BUY CULLINET 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Computer Associates International Inc. said today it will buy Cullinet Software 
Inc. for about $320 million in stock, a move that will strengthen its standing 
as the world's biggest independent software company. 
</P>
<P>
Computer Associates had $1.03 billion in revenue last year, becoming the first 
software company to reach the billion-dollar mark. Cullinet had revenue of $203 
million. 
</P>
<P>
Both companies get most of their revenue from software that runs on big 
mainframe computers made by International Business Machines Corp., although 
Computer Associates' appetite for acquisitions has carried it into other 
fields. 
</P>
<P>
Computer Associates is headed by Charles B. Wang, who has vowed to increase 
revenue by 30% a year. Its growth strategy has vaulted it ahead of such 
better-known companies as Microsoft Corp. and Lotus Development Corp. 
</P>
</TEXT>
